text:
Water is learned through the pang of thirst;
Land, through wide oceans you’ve traversed;
Rapture, through the stab of sharp agony;
Peace, through the wars fought to win it;
Love, through the dust on its old memorials;
Birds, through the hush of fresh snow.

source_text:
Water is taught by thirst;
Land, by the oceans passed;
Transport, by throe;
Peace, by its battles told;
Love, by memorial mould;
Birds, by the snow.

Earth would have been too much, I see,
And heaven not enough for me;
I should have had the joy
Without the fear to justify, --
The palm without the Calvary;
So, Saviour, crucify.

ORSINO:
What? Fear not to speak your thought.
Words are but holy as the deeds they cover:
A priest who has forsworn the God he serves;
A judge who makes Truth weep at his decree;
A friend who should weave counsel, as I now,
But as the mantle of some selfish guile;
A father who is all a tyrant seems,
Were the profaner for his sacred name.

Ah, sunflower, weary of time,
Who countest the steps of the sun;
Seeking after that sweet golden clime
Where the traveller’s journey is done;

text:
I’d carried hunger in my bones all those years;
my long-awaited noon had come, time to dine;
trembling, I dragged the table right up close,
and brushed my fingers against that unfamiliar wine.

source_text:
I had been hungry all the years;
My noon had come, to dine;
I, trembling, drew the table near,
And touched the curious wine.

text:
The hills hold a changed, unfamiliar cast;
Tyrian-hued light floods the entire village;
The dawn unfurls a wider, slower sunrise;
Dusk settles thicker, darker on the lawn;
A bright vermilion footprint pressed in new grass;
A purple-tinged finger stretches down the slope;
A brash, skittish fly taps against the window pane;
A spider’s back to tending his small weaving trade;
The rooster’s strut carries a new, bolder swagger;
The long-awaited flower peeks out everywhere you turn;
A sharp axe sings shrill and clear through the distant woods;
Fern scent hangs thick over untrampled, unused roads;
All this, and more I can’t find words to name,
That furtive, hush-hush air you’d know just as well,
And the old mystery tied to Nicodemus
Gets its soft, unspoken annual reply.

source_text:
An altered look about the hills;
A Tyrian light the village fills;
A wider sunrise in the dawn;
A deeper twilight on the lawn;
A print of a vermilion foot;
A purple finger on the slope;
A flippant fly upon the pane;
A spider at his trade again;
An added strut in chanticleer;
A flower expected everywhere;
An axe shrill singing in the woods;
Fern-odors on untravelled roads, --
All this, and more I cannot tell,
A furtive look you know as well,
And Nicodemus' mystery
Receives its annual reply.
